video_title: Primitive Technology: One-Way Blower Iron Smelt & Forging Experiment
comment_text:
The new blower produces more iron than the previous one. Using the same amount of ore and charcoal, a similar sized furnace and the same bloom processing method it makes 51g as opposed to 31 g of the previous design. The continuous blower is a big improvement over the intermittent spinning design (and this was only the first try). It's the most iron I've made in a single smelt yet.

The attempt to form a forgeable bar was disappointing although it was a better than expected casting. In the past I had successfully made forgeable iron by melting the prills in front of a blast rather than making a casting first. I will probably follow this method of decarburization rather than low temperature annealing in future.

The waste iron isn't lost however, I should be able to recycle it in future smelts as I've got a small pot of it. The waste iron from experiments could be re-smelted alone or added to future smelts to increase the yield.

video_title: Primitive Technology: One Way Spinning, Rope Stick Blower
comment_text: The key innovation with this blower is the one-way spinning technique which I developed through trial and error. Prior to this, my blowers would spin one way, stop, and then spin the other way during each cycle. With the new method, the stick and rope are pulled down and back on the power stroke causing the rotor to spin clockwise. Then the stick and rope are lifted up and forwards, loosening the ropes grip on the rotor, allowing it to continue to spin clockwise due to momentum. Thanks to the new mode of operation, continuous, one-way rotation is produced, conserving energy by not having rotation intermittently cease during each cycle and allowing for more efficient volute shaped housings to be used to direct the air as opposed to the old symmetrical housing design which were necessary for the old technique to work. The rope and stick are easier to make than a wheel and pulley used in modern forge blowers but the rpm and continuous one-way rotation of the 2 designs seem comparable.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Natural Draft Iron Smelt
comment_text: This is proof of concept that the natural draft furnace can make iron (the iron prills at the end of the video). I'd made a natural draft furnace before but this is the first time I was able to make any iron. There are many factors to getting a good smelt with this method but it is possible as there are records of natural draft iron smelting furnaces in ancient times. The benefit of such a furnace is the lack of bellows needed and so less labor is used. I've read these furnaces use more charcoal than forced draft furnaces which is understandable as the extra fuel is seemingly used to produce the draft. More experimenting needs to be done to obtain better iron yields but I think it's possible. Any questions about natural draft operation let me know. Thanks.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Volute Shaped Blower
comment_text: I tested the idea that some viewers suggested to make the blower hand cranked so that it spun in one direction only and to shape the housing to take advantage of this. It was suggested that even with the hand crank ratio of 1:1, the advantage would be apparent over the original intermittent high rpm blower powered with a string.  This blower prototype produced a high volume but low pressure air flow due to the sacrifice of rpm due to the 1:1 ratio. I did some rough calculations after making it and think that if the fan were scaled up to 1m as opposed to the 50 cm fan in the video, it might start to compete with the original blower design for the current rpm. I made a 1 m diameter fan but was unwieldy though it might have worked with more testing, time constraints prevented using it in this project. For now I'll stick to the previous blower design till I can increase the continuous rotation rpm with a durable mechanism. Or test positive displacement bellows and natural draft modes of air supply in up coming projects.

People asked last time how long a batch of 50 bricks takes so I recorded the time taken for each step:

Collecting/carrying 25 pots of clay to pit =1 hour
Collecting 3 pots of water and mixing in =10 minutes
Carry clay to floor = 20 minutes
Make 50 bricks = 30 minutes
Fix 2 bricks (that cracked while drying) =2 minutes
Turn bricks =1 minute
Collect wood = 1hour
Collect wood = 1 hour
Collect wood = 1 hour
Collect wood = 40 minutes
Total wood collecting time =3 hours 40 minutes
Stack kiln =15 minutes
Drying bricks fire =2 hours 45 minutes
Firing bricks = 3 hours
Bricks out = 10 minutes
Ash bricks = 15 minutes

video_title: Primitive Technology: Downdraft Kiln
comment_text: This is a down draft kiln, named after the fact that the flame goes up into the ware chamber before being drawn back down to the exit flue (hence down draft) before exiting the chimney. The idea is that only the coldest air leaves the chamber with the hottest staying up inside the kiln. So the kiln gets hotter than an updraft or cross draft kiln. Any questions feel free to ask.Thanks.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Roasted Ore and Shell Flux Smelt
comment_text: I tested roasting the ore, using lime flux (shells) and recycling slag in 3 separate smelts. Roasting the ore improved the yield about 2 times though this might have been due to decreasing the volume and effectively increasing the concentration of the ore. Adding lime (snail shells) ruined the smelt and produced next to no iron. This may be due to the ore already being basic and chemistry and the lime made it so basic that the slag won't flow. Sand (an acid flux) or old slag might make a better flux for this type of ore, lime might be better used to flux iron sand (acidic due to the silica content). Finally, I tested re-smelting the slag from previous smelts (not the slag from the lime smelt). The result was about half the iron came out compared to fresh ore, which suggests that slag should be smelted again to recover any iron not obtained during the first smelt if fresh ore is hard to come by. Thanks.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Roasted Ore and Shell Flux Smelt
comment_text:
Dear John.
As a metallurgy engineer that handles ore into kiln, I have the following advice:
I suggest you start with smaller fire and continuously build it up to increase the temperature, but it is important to keep a calm fire after starting it. Drying the ore slowly is the key to a nice and ready charge for the coal. Once you start adding coal (after 3-4 hours of drying the ore), I suggest you try making breaks while blowing, to let the coal and the charge cook well, like cooking a steak at a low temperature, because too much air will oxidize the iron earlier before it reaches a temperature near liquid phase before smelting, so that could be the problem why you are still getting small prills. Try making small pellets of 1 cubic centimeter of the ore. Burning the iron ore right from the start will cause the iron to pop and form into smaller prills into the slag.
Also lime is added in liquid metal only (from my experience so far)
Hope this helps!

video_title: Primitive Technology: Making Charcoal (3 Different Methods)
comment_text: I need more charcoal for smelting and metallurgy. These are the 3 methods I've used so far. The pit is the quickest and easiest to set up. But the mound and kiln produce better quality and larger pieces. All charcoal from these methods will work in smelting and forging but the 2 later methods make better fuel.  The advantage of the kiln over the mound is that it's re-useable and takes less effort to set up per batch than the mound does (less exposed wood to cover with mud). Also, I've started sieving the charcoal so all pieces used are over about 2.5 cm/1 inch. The larger lumps work better in furnaces because there are larger gaps between them that allow air to pass more easily through the fuel bed. This especially important in natural draft furnaces for smelting.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Iron Bacteria Cement (no fire/water insoluble)
comment_text: I came up with the idea of iron bacteria as a cement when I read that bog ore (a solid mineral) was formed from iron bacteria. So I shaped the bacteria into pinch pots and dried them to see if they set hard and wouldn't dissolve in water afterwards (remember no fire was used in this whole process). Surprisingly it worked and formed these water insoluble pots . I'm not sure on the chemistry behind it but I think it's due to water soluble iron 2 oxide in the bacteria becoming water insoluble iron 3 oxide when they dry out and oxidize. This reaction probably causes the material to cement together. It might be a useable mortar where iron bacteria is abundant.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Decarburization of iron and forging experiments
comment_text:
I think I figured out how to turn the brittle cast iron I've been producing into malleable iron that can be forged flat. When ever I smelt local ores it always produces cast iron prills rather than softer blooms of low carbon iron as one would expect from the bloomery process. I believe this because the prills are very hard, but when struck hard enough they shatter rather than flatten.

Cast iron is iron that has a high carbon content (when arranged by carbon content: Cast iron>Steel>iron). Cast iron has a lower melting point and is harder compared to regular iron. But it is more brittle so it's nearly impossible to forge. So I figured out how to decarburize it after some experiments. 

First I tried making an ingot to work on but it didn't cast properly. Then I tried rusting the iron to oxidize the metal before melting so it would decarburize the cast iron during the melt (similar to the "wet puddling" process in metallurgy). But this gave an incomplete melt also.

The method that finally worked was simply melting the cast iron in front of the air blast till the carbon burnt out in the oxygen rich zone of the forge. This caused the cast iron prills to melt together in a single blob that I then was able to hammer flat while yellow hot. 

This method is similar to the "stir fried steel/ ÁÇíÈí¢" process in ancient China or the "Osmond process" in Europe. It's done where ever cast iron needs to be converted to a lower carbon to be forged. I've seen videos about carburizing iron on youtube but none about decarburizing cast iron.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Cane Water Filter/Siphon
comment_text: I got the idea for this from MIT researchers who filtered water through a pine branch. Apparently it removes 99% of the bacteria in the process. What I added was the siphon principle, so that it's able to carry the water up and over an obstruction. Pottery isn't required for this to work, water could be siphoned and filtered from a higher up mud puddle into a lower container made of leaves for example. MIT article: https://meche.mit.edu/news-media/mit-engineers-make-filters-tree-branches-purify-drinking-water

video_title: Primitive Technology: Cane Water Filter/Siphon
comment_text: I conducted a similar experiment for a university course, using pine xylem to filter E. coli-contaminated water. My prototype was a bucket with multiple xylem spigots allowing the water to drip through with the assistance of gravity. We were amazed to find that it effectively removed the bacteria, as confirmed by an online E. coli testing kit. The water was deemed suitable for consumption

comment_text: Remember to turn on captions to see a description of what's happening. Experimenting with brick furnaces this time because they're quicker and easier to build than the in situ clay piled ones. They're also more portable, the height is easily adjusted (adding/subtracting bricks) and the bricks can be stored elsewhere when the furnace is not in use if space is an issue.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Smelting Iron In Brick Furnaces
comment_text: 10:47 - Fun fact, the water is what's actually "burning" here. Charcoal is a reducing agent, and can reduce hot steam into hydrogen and carbon monoxide, which then ignites due to the high temperatures inside the furnace. That's why the flames went crazy when the water was thrown into the furnace. This reaction only happens at temperatures above 1000¬∞C, so the furnace was at least that hot. This mix of hydrogen and carbon monoxide is called "water gas".

video_title: Primitive Technology: Making Iron From Creek Sand
comment_text: After making the iron knife from bacteria, I thought I'd investigate other, more ubiquitous sources of iron ore. The discovery that iron can be smelted from common sand in the creek is important because it means that special locations aren't required to have access to metal. Now the viewer should be able to locate a naturally occurring source of ore if they have access to a creek. Since learning this, I've never been to a creek that didn't have at least some magnetite in it.

video_title: Primitive Technology: Wood Ash Cement & Fired Brick Hut
comment_text:
In one of the Warhammer 40k science-fiction books there's a scene I've always liked. One of the characters is standing at the centre of a human space empire. Within the most important palace on Earth. And finds himself in a museum wing called "The Hall of Victories". Which is cherishing the accomplishments of human race in the distant space-faring future.

It contains a variety of technological achievements. Some military, most scientific. Such as the first stable human cloning formula. The first Titan rover. The first faster-than-light navigation circuit, etc. But in the middle of the museum is the centrepiece. A display case containing several shards of dented clay. Forming the outline of some sort of bowl.

Hundreds of thousands of years old.

The character expresses confusion at the placement. Pointing out that it's so simple a child could make it. But another character explains why it's so crucial. That without that bowl, all the other museum exhibits wouldn't exist. That at some point in the unrecorded past, one of our primitive ancestors noticed that a type of mud hardened when left in the sun. And he or she decided that they were going to MAKE something. That our journey as a species had those tentative first steps!

Primitive Technology feels like a celebration of those steps.

comment_text:
üí° Quick Note on Rebalancing & Tax
A viewer rightly pointed out that rebalancing inside a GIA (General Investment Account) can have tax implications and create extra admin because of the sell/buy orders. If your gains from those sales go over the annual CGT allowance (¬£3,000 in 2025/26), you‚Äôll need to report it on your self-assessment and pay Capital Gains Tax on the excess.

üëâ In my video I was referring specifically to rebalancing inside my ISA, where you don‚Äôt need to worry about those tax implications. To be clear, I personally avoid using the rebalance button often ‚Äî usually only once a year if allocations drift significantly.

So if you‚Äôre using a GIA, just be mindful that rebalancing has extra tax admin attached. As always, please do you own research.

comment_text: Rebalancing causes a lot of sells. This is OK inside an ISA but in a GIA it can cause a problem because you will have to work out the capital gains for your self-assessment tax form each year if it is over 3k of gains. You may have 50+ sell transactions in a tax year and you have to take into account the same day rule, 30-day rule and section 104 rule. Also, these rules apply across ALL your GIA accounts if you have GIAs with other brokers.  e.g. selling 10k SWDA on IE GIA and then buying 2k SWDA on Trading 212 on GIA Invest account within 30 days due to clicking 'rebalance' would mean the 30-day rule would apply. Because of this, I don't use Pies in GIAs.

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text: I am doing the same but for different  reasons. I got made redundant a decade ago, my first job back was with a small company and after that I became pigeonholed and in that decade I was made redundant a number of times so I gave up on pensions as often I had gone before the qualifying period whereas my ISA has remained steadfast.

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text: I contribute to both a workplace pension and a S&S ISA, but I prefer ISA for flexibility.

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text:
For clarity, Bengen's work looked at a 30-year American retirement (50% US stocks, 50% US bonds).  Its subsequent 4% rule refers to where the pot does not run out.  

Even a current average 45-year-old male in the UK is expected to live a further 40 years, with 25% chance of almost 50 years.  They may also have a state pension to factor in and will be invested completely differently to Bengen's research.  

Appreciate you have time to adjust plans given your age and the withdrawal flexibility you seem to be building up, but for older viewers just wanted to highlight this.

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text: I am paying 10% of my wages into a work place pension. Really considering using it to 13%. Also going to add ¬£300 a month into my stocks and shares isa. I like both methods

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text: Was relieved to see it's not either/or for you and in fact both with good reasons for prioritising the ISA. Another good reason to maybe prioritise an ISA is if you have some certainty in a windfall in the next three years. Maybe a big bonus that's likely, employer share option scheme maturing, gift or releasing equity. An ISA is use it or lose it whereas a pension you can go back and use unclaimed allowances up to three years. If you know you're going to have some excess cash in a couple of years then use the ISA to its fullest now and retrospectively use your pension allowance when you get the windfall later.

video_title: Why I'm prioritising my ISA over my Pension (ISA vs Pension 2025)
comment_text:
As you should anyway. ISA is yours to do with as you like, when you like (provided you don‚Äôt have one of these horrible LISAs).

Pension funds have set retirement dates and the rules could change at any point.  They could go back to the old system where you are forced to take an annuity on your retirement date (yuck, yuck, yuck‚Ä¶ sucks to be you if your retirement date is during a bear market which is down 10% month to month). 

I‚Äôm fully against pension schemes‚Ä¶ horrible things‚Ä¶ mostly terribly managed (I did a seat in a large law firm defending them, so I‚Äôve seen how the big names treat their ‚Äúclients‚Äù).  Returns are pretty poor and just a way to extract fees from everyday chumps.

video_title: How Much Car Can You Really Afford in Canada? (By Salary)
comment_text:
You can do so well in used-car hunting if you look for cars where the manufacturer did really well but for one reason or another the market didn't appreciate the vehicle. In especially competitive segments like, say, small- or mid-size crossovers or SUVs, the most popular vehicle usually gets the most sales but is often only slightly better than the competition. This has allowed me to buy cars that I ENJOY DRIVING, and that are very well-equipped for Canadian winters, and so I don't feel like I'm suffering or just getting by.

Then you maintain them with all the money you're saving from not making car payments, or at least not such large ones, and you can drive some of these things forever.

I still drive my 2009 Acura TL with over 340,000 km on the clock. Aside from consumables (brakes, tires) and service interval items (timing belt, water pump, spark plugs) I've had to replace a wheel bearing and a radiator. At the 300,000 km mark I did a big suspension refresh: shocks/struts, swaybar bushings, and swaybar links which made the car ride like new again. I bought the car in 2013 with 79,000 km for half its new price. It was a one-owner West Coast lease return (I live in Alberta) and had sat on the lot for nearly four months because the "power plenum" grille was very controversial -- the big ugly beak on Acuras of that era caused the TL, a magnificent car, to depreciate rapidly, which was to my advantage. Put all-weather (not all-season) tires on a SH-AWD TL and you are simply unstoppable in Canadian winters. It's unreal. You can find a low-mileage 4th-gen TL now for LESS than I paid in nominal dollars for it 12 years ago, and inflation has made that a very cheap price indeed; in 2012 I paid $24k and I routinely see low-mileage examples under $18k.

Three years ago we replaced an end-of-life Volvo with a 2018 Lincoln MKX Reserve 2.7L. Also four years old with 78,000 km. I had been watching a review of the Genesis GV70 and was impressed by all the features: twin-turbo V6 power; great stereo; massaging seats. It started me wondering if there wasn't a less-loved competitor that performed nearly as well. For two generations, Lincoln had been tarting up the Ford Edge and trying to get Lexus money for them. With the 3rd-gen MKX they finally got serious about making good cars again; in 2019 the MKX was rebadged the Nautilus and given a new front fascia and swapped the 6-speed for a newer 8-speed but inside it is the identical car. The Revel Ultima stereo--the best of 3 available sound systems, which even Lincoln dealers sometimes label wrong, so do your homework--is simply the best I've ever heard, and I DJed for 17 years when I was younger and used to run competition car audio in the 90s. I paid $27,900 for what, four years earlier, had been a $74,000 car. My MKX had been traded into a Lexus dealership and came with a full service history; the original owner had had everything, down to every oil change, done at the dealer.

And so on. I pointed out to my teenage and young-adult kids that even if I just replaced the Acura every five years with another, four-year-old used car, it would have eaten up money that we instead have spent on family trips to France, Barbados, and Singapore. And the money I've saved compared to buying new? My retirement accounts have earned over $100k in that time on the back of money I didn't spend on new vehicles.

All this is just trying to bolster the message of the video with some specific examples. You can get really, really great pricing on vehicles that have top safety ratings from the IIHS, great reliability (with forums full of solutions to common problems), and are a lot of fun to drive in exchange for a few dozens of hours of homework. It can be some of the most financially valuable time you ever spend.

video_title: How Much Car Can You Really Afford in Canada? (By Salary)
comment_text: When rules are suggested, such as the 35% rule, it should be stated clearly if the income is before or after taxes. The largest expense for most people is taxation, it draws down to a much lower usable income. If you earn $250K in BC, you will take in only $161K after taxes, that's a big tax hit, enough to spend $89K on a new car every year, if you earn $150K each year, you will take in only $107K, the tax hit is enough to spend almost  $43K on a new car every year.

video_title: 15 Reasons to Leave Canada Forever
comment_text: It's not just how high the taxation is, it's what is taxed that is even worse. They are heavily taxing businesses and investments. On paper, it looks somewhat reasonable, but in reality it is not.  Operating a business and investing your money, means you are taking a risk, what the tax does is reduce the risk to reward ratio, less reward means you are less willing to take the leap, and that has a repressive effect on innovation, competitiveness, and the economy in general. If you reinvest earnings, there's no break at all, you'll still be taxed as usual, leaving you with less money to reinvest, which is counterproductive. The small business tax rate seems reasonable, until you realize it's only applicable on up to $500K profit, an amount that in today's business world, is a very small amount of money, the threshold is outdated and far too low. In addition, the tax on earnings that eventually make it to the shareholders, is taxed at the highest rate, there are no breaks at all for the people who take the risks and operate businesses. For investors, the taxation on cap gains is significantly higher than is widely advertised, it is more than the 50% inclusion with 50+% deducted, it's more like the 2/3 inclusion despite the 2/3 inclusion being dropped. What Mark Carney's government did after dropping the 2/3 inclusion increase, was to secretly increase it again, using the largely unknown AMT, bringing it back up to almost the same as before - thanks for nothing Mark Carney! I do plan to keep voting, except this time with my feet, and with my money. There's an exit tax to leave Canada, however, I can keep my money in Canada, and move my business somewhere else, it will be the ultimate middle finger to a backwards repressive tax system that I am thoroughly fed up with. The super high tax I pay, would not be so bad if I qualified for all the programs my tax money is paying for, except each year, it seems less becomes available because after you earn a certain amount, you'll no longer qualify, yet they expect you keep on paying the most in taxes. Thanks for nothing, Canada! I'm not even against paying taxes, all I want to see is fairness, and a much less repressive counterproductive taxation system put in place. I do NOT want to leave Canada, but from a business point of view, it makes sense to leave.

video_title: Why You Might REGRET Leaving Canada Forever
comment_text:
Departure tax is basically a tax on unrealized capital gains. So if you don't have anything that is subject to capital gains tax, you won't pay the exit tax. (TFSAs, RSPs, cash in the bank, primary residence are all exempt from the departure tax.) I left Canada a few years ago, declared non-residency and was out of the country for 6 years and never filed an income tax return in 5 of those 6 years (the year before you leave you file your last tax return).

I kept my drivers licence active during this time. (I even renewed it when I came back to Canada for a family visit!). I also kept my 3 bank accounts and 4 credit cards. And I never informed my credit cards or banks that I had moved abroad. Why? They have no right to know that. Everything is online. I get my statements and pay them online. There's absolutely no reason for them to know I'm abroad.

I had to return to Canada because my mom got ill and I needed to look after her. When I returned to Canada, I simply started paying taxes again. There was absolutely zero issue from keeping all of these other things active in Canada and I never heard from CRA or my banks.

The only big issue I encountered when I returned was getting my provincial health insurance back. I gave them the proof they wanted but it was always never good enough. I went in about 5 times and they kept wanting other documents. In other words, they kept moving goal posts.

When I was rejected on my fifth visit, I was so fed up with dealing with them that my dad suggested I go to my local MLA/MPP to complain. Despite the fact that he was a Conservative and the Liberals were the government, he managed to get the Ontario Health Minister directly involved with my case, who gave the healthy ministry hell. Because within 48 hours (after being rejected) the local provincial health office called me up and said: "Come on in. You have been approved."

WOW!!! Who would have thought that governments sometimes actually serve the people ... and in such a direct way!




So, if you do come back and have a problem getting your health card back ... if you're following all the rules, and they still give you the run-around I highly recommend contacting your local MLA or MPP (depending on the province). Remember, they're there to serve you!

comment_text:
‚úàThinking of leaving Canada? Don‚Äôt let the CRA take more than they should. Most people make at least one costly mistake when leaving Canada. Grab our free guide on the 7 biggest CRA tax traps, and how to avoid them.

üì• Download it here üëâ https://blueprintfinancial.ca/exit-canada-tax-guide-download

video_title: How Non-Resident Canadians Use Offshore Corps to Pay 0% Tax (Legally)
comment_text:
Speaking as someone who has been a non-resident Canadian, you are allowed to keep bank accounts in Canada. You're even allowed to keep your drivers licence. The big things are getting rid of your house (or renting it to a person that is "arms length" away from you, i.e., not a family member). You also need to have residency in another country (and be able to prove that with official ID), before Canada will let you go. And CRA will determine the date you left to be the last of these 3 dates: (1) The date you left; (2) the date your spouse and dependents left, if applicable; and (3) the date you became a resident of another country. If you already have residency in another country and have no dependents or spouse, then it all boils down to the date you left will be considered the date you became a non-resident.

Also to note ... the exit / departure tax is only a tax on "unrealized capital gains" (as he mentions in the video). If all your assets are in cash and sitting in the bank, even if you have $1 Billion of cash, you will not have to pay this exit tax, as cash has already been taxed. My suggestion is to sell everything and reacquire once you've left. That way, when you sell it, you'll pay capital gains tax on it when you sell it and, when you leave, all you'll have is the cash from those sales of assets.

And remember ... your primary home is not subject to capital gains tax and, as such, is also exempt from this exit tax. Likewise, RSPs, RIFs and TFSAs are exempt as well. And, if you have RSPs or RIFs and you're moving abroad, I'd ask your accountant which countries does Canada allow you to withdraw these savings when you move there. Years ago (when I moved abroad in 2006), you could have moved to Ireland and simply withdraw all your RSPs/RIFs into a simple savings bank account in Ireland as a lump sum, while just paying a 10% withholding tax in Canada (which of course saves you a ton in taxes over your retirement years). This is no longer an option, but there might be other nations you can move to that Canada will allow you to do this with. And once you have your cash in a bank account, you won't ever have to pay tax on that money again. And you can invest in whatever you want without issues like you would if you had kept that money in your RSP.

video_title: This TFSA Trick Can Unlock Big GIS Money (Until the CRA Bans It!)
comment_text:
Its normal TFSA isn't counted as income since it WAS counted as income when you first earned the money.
Its normal you're not taxed on it since you WERE already taxed on it at first.
Its just the opposite of RRSP which tax you later. TFSA you pay up front with the benefit that it will be more favorable in the future.
The gov won't do anything about it and the reason is very simple.
Right now you can invest into an RRSP to lower your income tax. This manouver can make you eligible for low income benefits since your taxable income for the year goes under a treshhold.
TFSA is the same thing, except in reverse. Since you didn't get access to the extra low income benefits during the years you invested, its normal that you get this benefit later.
In gaming language, its just a different playstyle which provide the same benefits, but differently/at a different point in life.

Examples you earn 60k a year :
RRSP : if you put 20k per year (not that this doesn't work forever since there is a cap, so its only ''good'' if you didn't save while yonger), then your taxable income becomes 40k
At 40k you become a low income person and benefit from about 2k extra non taxable $ from gov programs.
This means that you basically have the effective income of about 43-44k in addition to your 20k RRSP. You also get tax back from the 20k since you paid too much through payroll. Around 7k extra (net). This mean that even tho you saved 20k in RRSP, at the end of the day, you still had about 54-55k gross income to live with. Your RRSP was basically 75% off compared to someone who made 60k but didn't put any money in the RRSP.

TFSA : if you put 20k in your TFSA (also doesn't work forever, but I just make big numbers so its easier to explain the impact), your taxable income remains 60k.
You do not qualify for any low income person program and you pay taxes on the whole 60k EVEN THOUGH you didn't have 60k to live with.
Also your TFSA turning from 50k or 100k into millions of $$ in entirely speculative as it COULD also plummet to 0$. Of course we only talk about the 3 people with insane luck.
Regardless, you took the financial hit early on, paying more tax than anyone who made a salary of 40k (you paid taxes on the extra 20k of income).
And this is extremely difficult. The money you put in the TFSA is NET, which mean that for the purpose of this video, in order to put 20k NET in the TFSA, you had to live with about 60% of your income. The lifestyle between 100% income and 60% income is HUGE, considering flat fees like rent, grocery and etc can only get so low.

And that kind of sacrifice definitely deserves being able to have an amazing retirement IMO.

video_title: The Truth About Retiring With $500,000 in Canada
comment_text:
Christopher, I appreciate the holistic perspective you take here. Financial success at retirement, absent some life-changing windfall, is the product of a large number of good choices, big and small, over a lifetime.  And choices are often driven by factors that are not really financial at all: whether a person takes the long view or lives for the moment, their financial literacy, sees value in life as defined by simple pleasures and not merely owning things, is able to distinguish between wants and needs, and other such matters of personality and self-awareness. 

To borrow a line from Joseph Campbell, it's the financial equivalent of the hero's journey.

That's not to say that life doesn't impose certain constraints, be it our income, our job, operating costs to maintain existence, and unexpected financial setbacks like job loss, illness, or divorce. But for many, there is a certain amount of room between our income and our overhead, and it's how we behave in that space -- notably around savings rate, investing, time in the market, and being disciplined about spending -- that decides whether we are a "Ben" or a "Jerry." 

Here's to all of us being a little more like Jerry!

comment_text:
Comparing one‚Äôs personal savings to those of others is ultimately a futile exercise, as each individual‚Äôs financial landscape is shaped by unique variables‚Äîmost notably, their cost of living. What truly matters is not the absolute value of your savings, but whether those savings are aligned with the life you lead and the expenses you incur. Whether one has $1,000 or $1 million set aside is immaterial if their spending outpaces their income or reserves. Financial security is not a function of how much you have‚Äîit is a function of how wisely and sustainably you manage what you have.

On a side note, if you want a wake up call, visit one or two retirement homes in your area and inquire about the cost per month.  Even the ‚Äúcheapest‚Äù option is often well over $5,000 a month- getting older is expensive and knowing this earlier, rather than later may help motivate you to spend less, save more now.

comment_text:
As I've gotten a little bit older I realized that while I still absolutely despise the hell that is called 'working', it just isn't practical to do traditional FIRE at a young age like 35 or so like I originally wanted.  Its just way too much money.  People take shortcuts by using a 4% rule which I think is sketchy and/or being ultra lean and not being able to afford anything.

I REALLY like the Flamingo approach of hitting 50% and then backing off and not caring about rushing the finish line as much.  Best strategy in my opinion.

I also will add that I think that anyone who hits like 200k only and calls themselves Coast FIRE by doing math tricks that require four decades of hopeful growth; is an idiot.

video_title: I've had a HUGE Realisation!! This changes our FINANCIAL INDEPENDENCE Plan!!
comment_text:
I think ‚Äògoing hard‚Äô when you have children is challenging. By the time you have the money to do things the kids are too old for the activity or not interested. We‚Äôve always travelled with our boys for that reason. But saved and paid cash for all holidays - nothing worse to me than continuing to pay (and pay more $ overall) for holidays long after they are a memory.
But we can always revisit our plans and adjust as we need and to what suits us at the time.

video_title: I've had a HUGE Realisation!! This changes our FINANCIAL INDEPENDENCE Plan!!
comment_text:
That's awesome. 

While watching your incredible video's over the last year, I always had in the back of my mind that your approach was quite aggressive and that there would be a cost to it.  Obviously I stayed quiet as it is none of my business how people approach their financial plans.  But this video has pretty much confirmed what I thought, and I totally agree with your new thoughts.  

I'm having to be aggressive on my end due to mismanagement of my previous working life.  I'm far behind where you are at and am slightly older at 42.  So, I just have to buckle down.  But once I get to a certain stage, I'm taking my foot off the peddle - we need to enjoy our lives while we are young enough to do all the things we want to do.  Lived experiences is worth more than all the money in the world.

Case in point.  My Aunt (mums sister) visits from Scotland every couple of years; I take a break from my finances to provide both of them with travel experiences in Australia.  It sets me back a wee bit financially, but to build those experiences with important people that won't be around one day is so important to me.  And also to build experiences and memories for family that are younger - my nieces for instance - so when I'm gone one day, they will be able to reflect back with a smile (I hope).

It's a balancing act in the end.  I really hope that this new direction for you does improve your personal happiness.  From one over-thinker to another over-thinker... Good luck!

comment_text:
What is more disappointing than the dropping stock market?  The amount of spam comments that are appearing on YouTube.  Hope they do something about this soon!

My Net Worth has dropped about $20,000.  But it's all on paper, nothing is realised.  I see it as an opportunity to put money into my ETF's at a cheaper price.  I think that's the way we have to look at things.  The only people that really hurt are those that need the money today and have to sell at a lower price = potentially at a loss.

Glad to see your house valuation doing so well.  What do you think about the future though - a lot of doomsayers saying a large housing correction is on the way, do you think this will happen?  I think again, it doesn't truly matter in your situation as it is your family home - again it's worth is mostly just a paper figure that means little until you need to sell.  Obviously can help when it comes to negotiating better deals with the banks, but it looks like you are already across that. 

(My crystal ball) I think the stock markets will rebound leading up to the end of 2023, not as dramatic as during COVID, but still quite strong.  And I do think their will be a correction in the housing market, too many over-leveraged people not prepared for interest rate rises and the house prices went up far too much in such a short space of time for this to be sustainable.  But we shall see - I just hope it is a soft landing for most Aussies no matter what happens.

comment_text:
My plan (note I do not have a mortgage....... yet):

- Keep putting $1200 per fortnight into my partners trading account.  She can't work, so we have it under her name for tax minimisation purposes.
- Do not purchase any shares (ETFs) until we have got confirmation that the bear market has stopped. 
- Be a fantastic tenant to our landlord to keep our rent well below the market - he has just raised it by $50 per week, but it's still good value.  $400/week in Gympie for a 4x2.
- Hope that the increasing interest rates bring down that inflated property bubble over the next 24 - 36 months.  Will be looking for a bargain. 
- Sell 2/3s of our ETFs when the time is right to purchase a property. 

There is a bit of speculation in there, but as long as we are flexible I reckon we can get a win.  
I have mixed feelings about those people that borrowed to the hilt at inflated house prices and are now going to really struggle to keep their heads above water.  This is where financial education has let so many down.  But I'll be angry if they get too much support from the government, which in turn keeps the bubble inflated and punishes those that are diligently saving and living within their means to get into property.  

The previous Federal Government, the banks and the RBA have a lot to answer for.  In my opinion.

comment_text: Great video. One of the big things alot of finance enthusiasts push is the delayed gratification at an early age. Spending a decade in your 20's saving money and putting it away works incredibly well as the two largest contributing factors to compound interest is 1. How much are you starting with? (presumably large if you're spending a decade saving religiously) and 2. How long have you got (again presuming at 30 years old you still have another 30 years before needing the money for retirement).

video_title: Why The First $100k is the Hardest (MIND BLOWING!) Compound Interest & Charlie Munger
comment_text:
I think another part that makes that first $100k the hardest (at least for myself personally) was that it needed to be divided into certain foundation accounts - an emergency fund for instance of $20k.  These funds couldn't be invested into riskier places like the stock market as it needed to be stable and quickly accessible if needed.

Therefore that first lot of money was slowed down greatly from decent compounding which dragged out the process a bit.

However, it needed to be done to ensure I bulletproofed my life.

comment_text:
I know that for some people, the gym is a must for social and motivation reasons.  But this is definitely a big expense that I reckon you can get away from. 

I just save up some splurge money to get dumbbells or other equipment periodically.  I've got one adjustable bench, and dumbbells ranging from 1kg to 20kg that I've collected over the last year - it doesn't use up much space at all.  Living up in Gympie, I get a good cardio workout just by power walking the hilly roads from where I live - to the Mary River and back - giving me 15,000 steps with fresh air and some beautiful scenery.  Also rubber bands - they are an amazing light weight / portable solution if you are away from home.

Push ups - free, jumping jacks - free, running on the spot - free, ab crunches - free, lunges/squats - free....... I think I've made my point.  The gym in my opinion is a luxury, not a necessity. But again, I understand for some people it may be part of their identity - and all power to them.

video_title: This will change EVERYTHING you think about SAVING and INVESTING // DIE WITH ZERO by BILL PERKINS!
comment_text: I think the 0.7 formula is just so simple, it confuses you because you overthink it. Basically, he skips over the step of calculating how much money you need to live the rest of your life, and that is multiply your living costs x years ahead. So if you need 50.000 a year and you are going to live 10 years, you need 500.000. But because the money is growing in investments, you don't need to have the whole amount up front, so he ran some numbers and came up with the idea that you only need about 70% of that number up front. The money will grow up to the need as you go. Thus you multiply the target by 0.7

comment_text: Another fabulous video. I agree with other comments no one talks bout specific details . It is incredibly helpful seeing your family finances, real life example. comment_text: Hi, I ran into your channel when I was searching for NAB equity builder and was amazed by the detail and transparency about your family finance. There are many investment videos on YouTube but few from Aussie perspective or as ordinary mom and dad. We are almost at the same age and in comparable financial position. And what's more interesting is that I also live in Brisbane. I started investing earlier but never know how other families are doing, even closest friends'. People just don't talk about it. Glad to witness your journey, and please keep on the good job. Cheers!

video_title: We Have INCREASED our SAVINGS RATE and are SAVING One Income // Financial Independence Retire Early!
comment_text: My favorite video of yours this far! We've lived below one income for 7 years as we decided I'd stay home with our girls till they are young teens, at first it was purely because of our values but in the last 4 years we've been able to live on just 70% of one income so when I return to work the excess pay will feel crazy! We'll start to invest my whole income then. Can't wait! And I'll only be 35 when my 4 kids are teensüòÅ so I feel like we've got some time still. Mortgage is on track to be paid in full when I am 39, 9.5 years remaining

comment_text:
Great video, thans for being so transparent, I want to do what you do, but seems impossible. I've checked my expenses and I have a million questions based on my expenses:

I assume you don't have any pets or a water filter that needs replacing every year?
What is the cost of maintaining your pool?
Do you buy any gifts at Xmas for anybody?
Do you do annual pest control?
Do you have home and contents insurance?
What about when you need something from the chemist?
What about your clothes, or a pair of shoes, etc?
Do you or your husband do any sports?
What about white good maintenance or replacement?

Sorry for so many questions, I just admire what you do and want to emulate it and these are some of the expenses that found in my budget that you don't have in this video.

comment_text:
I was introduced to the BPS model at a family therapy session for my mum.

It was very helpful. There's different variations of it, you'll see on Google - a couple of things that might need adding are "Age" to bio and "Cultural background" to social.

And cultural background also presents challenges particularly if for example like in some my life history, you perhaps spend a little too much time with friends who aren't really "friends" from a different cultural background.

I'm sure you all understand me there.

video_title: IB TOK EXPLAINED Ep 3: Why you cannot say that ‚Äúhuman sciences are subjective‚Äù
comment_text:
A very good presentation and worthy attempt to resolve the problem of "the social sciences". However at times you seem to use the word "study" as if it can be conflated with the word "science". Of course it cannot. Study is necessary to science, but science is not necessary to study. Take, for example, an artist's study. "Human sciences" would more accurately be described as "human studies", if for no other reason than the fact that the studies themselves can grossly affect what is being studied (and yes I have heard of Schroedinger's Cat, but that is not a gross effect). For example, any so-called "scientific theory" of economics, once widely understood by economists, will affect the way the economy behaves on a macro level. Why? Because economists will implement the theory to "run" (i.e. affect) economies. As a result, yet another theory of economics will need to be created to encompass how these interactions between human theories and economies is affecting the outcome of what is being studied. You see the problem? This is a recursive process, where social "scientists" end up studying their own backsides. One can scientifically study human behaviour, of course, but trying to construct a scientific theory behind the reasons behind that behaviour, i.e.trying to apply science to subjective human experience, necessarily requires unsubstantiated and unverifiable storytelling that can itself affect how the subject behaves. 

The above does not hold for scientific theories, for example "what happens inside a black hole". They cannot affect the way a black hole behaves. The other difference here is a scientific theory will allow very accurate predictions based on that theory (for example the curvature of light around the sun) where accurate measurements can potentially support or completely falsify the theory. If a theory of human behaviour is not falsifiable, then it is not a scientific theory.

Or to put it another way, dreams are nature's way of telling us not everything in human experience has to make rational sense.

comment_text: KOC, there is an even better possibility for the in-season tournament - building rivalries. In the WNBA, it has been very connected to the finals, but not in the way you said. In 2022, the Aces won the cup, and then won the finals. Then, in 2023, the Liberty beat the Aces for the cup. But then, in the finals, the Aces beat the Liberty for the championship. So it was a rematch. Likewise, in 2024, the Lynx beat the Liberty for the cup, but then in the finals, the Liberty beat the Lynx for the championship. So, storylines like that have really amped up the interest in the in-season tournament, because the WNBA doesn't typically have random teams winning it.

video_title: TRICK or TREAT with Adam Mares: Which NBA Trends Are Here to Stay?
comment_text:
NBA cup has to be fixed for it to ever matter. 1st thing you have to count the final toward the regular season. Guarantee a lot of players, even though they've been coached to say the right things, don't care or even don't want to make the final because they don't want an extra in-season scrimmage that doesn't count. (Even the stats don't count!) 2nd the group stage is terrible, starting 5 games into the season and stretched out over 5 weeks. It's not even a tournament, just a bunch of random games. The best teams over that stretch can lose the wrong night and not advance. No one's ever going to care much about 8 teams advancing from having won a few random games to a playoff many don't care about advancing in.

Start it 35 or so games into the season and make it a real tournament with consecutive games so the best teams advance so you'll have the champion of the 1st half of the season, count the whole thing toward the regular season, and replace the all-star game with the 1st half championship and you might have something.

There are plenty of coaches like this across sports, like Pete Carroll and Thibodeau ..... but Thibodeau was just a bit better at it and cared about a few specific things like shot selection. video_title: Are the Dodgers DONE After Game 5 Collapse?
comment_text: From a lifelong Jays fan, its not over. We just watched the Jays comeback from 0-2 and the 2-3 against the Mariners in the ALCS. I remember the Jays losing in 7 games to George Brett and the KC Royals after taking a 3 - 1 lead in the ALCS in 1985. Until the 27th out in the last game of the season, itss not over. The Dodgers will start the most dominate starter in the 2025 post season in Yamamoto. This series is far from over, but Dodgers fans should be worried they wont get their back to back championships.

video_title: Are the Dodgers DONE After Game 5 Collapse?
comment_text: It is the fundamental aspect of baseball. Teams focus too much on launch angle and analytics and ignore how the game used to be played. Make contact, move runners, reduce the strike out ratio. That's all the Jays did and it worked against Yanks, Ms, and Dodgers. You can't win by strike out 10 to 15 times every game and expect to win with HRs. Hope more teams realize that and shift back to  old ways of emphasizing level swing, put balls in play, move runners, and etc can produce more wins especially in the playoffs.

video_title: Are the Dodgers DONE After Game 5 Collapse?
comment_text: The fact that Yesavage is a rookie speaks to his composure and mental strength but not to his ability. It is already apparent that his pitching is on an elite level with the best in baseball. This was not a one-off as he had already demolished a Yankee lineup with some very good hitters in the ALDS, going 5 no-hit innings with 11 strikeouts - and the reason he went all the way from pitching in A-ball to starting in the World Series in one season is because he simply refused to stop striking out everybody in the minor leagues - he would strike out the hitters, then he would strike out the opposing manager and coaching staff, then the umpires and some of the families that had come to watch the game. He was a strikeout menace so they had to promote him before things really got out of hand.

comment_text: Aerospace engineer here, using gas turbine engines for power is very common for many uses not just data center. This simifies the manufacturing pipeline vs having unique designs for power gen

comment_text: Neuroscientist here. All purported ‚Äúneural interfaces‚Äù (inc NIA and any newer non-invasive analogues) measure muscle tension and eye movements, not brain. To measure brain you need close to full head coverage for the physics to work properly (solving the inverse problem) and you also need very expensive high resolution amplifiers bc the brain signal is many orders of magnitude smaller than the noise caused by muscles/eyes.

comment_text: 3:16 I understand the concept of competing for your consumer‚Äôs time but there is a fundamental difference in how games work as opposed to tv, streaming, and ‚Äúshort form video.‚Äù They are passive-engagement activities whereas gaming is an active-engagement activity. Sure they share similar electronic mediums but the participation requirement for gaming is closer to that of a sport. Watch a video of any length is like a fan of a sport in the bleachers. Playing a video game is like a player on the field of that sport. A player doesn‚Äôt just leave the field to get food whenever they want like a fan can because active engagement doesn‚Äôt allow for that, if you want to be proficient or at least effective. This mindset Microsoft has is fundamentally flawed.

video_title: 10 Hidden Gaming Easter Eggs With POWERFUL Rewards
comment_text: Ah yes, Aerondight. The sword of Sir Lancelot, one of the most unknightly knights who was ever knighted. Okay, maybe that's a bit harsh, but when your claim to fame is sleeping with the queen, were you really knight material in the first place? I suppose that makes Aerondight an oddly appropriate sword for Geralt.

video_title: 10 Hidden Gaming Easter Eggs With POWERFUL Rewards
comment_text: There is one broken weapon I remember using. In Saints Row 4 if you shoot a door to the Let's Pretend shop there will be a easter egg basement you can visit. Down there among the cuttouts of the dev team you can get The Noisy Cricket. It's a Men in Black Reference weapon that does indeed send you flying the moment you shoot it in an explosion just like Will Smith in the movie. But the up side is that the gun recharges meaning you don't have to buy more ammo for it or hope to get more in the map and can be upgraded to recharge faster.

video_title: 10 Video Games That Punished You For Buying Them
comment_text: The game that comes to mind for me is a little robot game from 2018 called Shiny. What I thought I'd be getting based on the Amazon page was sort of an off-brand Clank without Ratchet style game. What I got was a dreadful, hyper-industrial side scrolling platformer. The genre subversion would have been fine. Except the game had no apparent storyline whatsoever, all the warmth and charm of an uninstalled crankshaft and controls that felt like an afterthought.  It probably was technically better than most of the games on this list but I don't think I've ever kicked myself harder for buying a game in my life.
